<h2>The heat wave 'Lucifer' in southern Europe</h2>
<br><br>
In early autumn 2017, Europe is recovering from the soaring temperatures during the 2017 summer 'Lucifer' heat wave. Especially southern Europe saw the effects of this heat wave. Figure 1 (left panel) shows for this summer the largest number of consecutive days where the daily maximum temperature was above the 90th percentile - the Warm Spell Duration Index. The right panel of Figure 1 shows the precipitation in summer 2017 as a fraction of the climatological mean amount. It shows the dry conditions in all European countries around the Mediterranean, the Balkan and into the Ukraine.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_heat_wave_duration_index_wrt_mean_of_reference_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-08-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_heat_wave_duration_index_wrt_mean_of_reference_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-08-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc__2017-08-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc__2017-08-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc__2017-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc__2017-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Shown is the Warm Spell Duration Index (WSDI, left panel) and the fraction of precipitation with respect to the 1981-2010 climatology (right panel). The WSDI is defined as the number of consecutive days in the summer (June, July, August) of 2017 where the daily maximum temperature is higher than the (locally defined) 90th percentile. This reference value is calculated for a five day window centred on each calendar day of a given 30 year climate reference period.</em>
<br><br>
In summer 2017 temperatures were mostly above the long term mean with a maximum of more than +5 &#176;C over the Balkans and Spain. Scandinavia showed the lowest temperature anomalies. Portugal was hot - it saw the 9th hottest summer since 1931 - and extremely dry - the 3rd driest on record. Two heat waves were observed in Portugal. Temperatures in Spain this summer reached the second rank (since 1956, after 2003) with a deviation of +1.6 &#176;C above the average of 1981-2010. Spain and France reported five heat waves for this summer. Most of Italy was also affected by heat waves and the drought in southern and central Italy persisted to one year and water reservoirs were getting empty. The drought and water shortage increased the number of wild fires and reduced the agricultural yields, which was also the case on the Balkan peninsula, where summer air temperature in Croatia were +2.4 to +4.0 &#176;C higher than usual. Serbia saw its second warmest summer on record with highest daily maximum temperature of 41.6 &#176;ะก on 6 August and six recorded heat waves. Slovakia reported two heat waves where in Bratislava summer air temperature was the 2nd highest since 1931. Summer was also hot in the Republic of Moldova, where August temperatures reached +39 &#176;ะก - a once in 15 year value. While the recorded summer temperatures in the Republic of Moldova are observed about once every 10 years for the entire observation period, these temperatures are now more frequently occurring on average of once every 3 years.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/sep2017/rcc_eude_swe_ttt_hw_bub_aktuell.png"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2017/rcc_eude_swe_ttt_hw_bub_aktuell.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Severity of heat wave 'Lucifer' with respect to other heat waves in the past.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>The weather in September 2017</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
September 2017 temperatures were below average for a large part of the continent, while for the north and especially the east, the temperatures were very high. When comparing the observed temperatures to percentile thresholds, the daily maximum and minimum temperatures turned out to be exceptionally above average (over the 90th percentile), with the emphasis over eastern Ukraine. The area where the average daily minimum temperatures where exceptionally above average extends up to Scandinavia and is considerably larger than the rather confined area where averaged daily maximum temperature is exceptionally above average.
<br><br>
Monthly averaged temperatures in northern Italy, parts of central Europe and southwest France have been much below average while in particular daily minimum temperatures in Spain and Portugal have been low as well.
